#: ../../source/fundamentals/dependency-injection.rst:2
msgid "Custom providers"
msgstr "定制供应商"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/dependency-injection.rst:4
msgid ""
"There are a lot of scenarios when you might want to bind something "
"**directly** to the Nest inversion of control container. For example, any"
" constant values, configuration objects created based on the current "
"environment, external libraries, or pre-calculated values that depends on"
" few other defined providers. Moreover, you are able to override default "
"implementations, e.g. use different classes or make use of various test "
"doubles (for testing purposes) when needed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/dependency-injection.rst:12
msgid ""
"One essential thing that you should always keep in mind is that Nest uses"
" **tokens** to identify dependencies. Usually, the auto-generated tokens "
"are equal to classes. If you want to create a custom provider, you’d need"
" to choose a token. Mostly, the custom tokens are represented by either "
"plain strings or symbols. Following best practices, you should hold those"
" tokens in the separated file, for example, inside ``constants.ts``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/dependency-injection.rst:20
msgid "Let’s go through the available options."
msgstr "Let’s go through the available options."

#: ../../source/fundamentals/dependency-injection.rst:23
msgid "Use value"
msgstr "Use value"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/dependency-injection.rst:25
msgid ""
"The ``useValue`` syntax is useful when it comes to either define a "
"constant value, put external library into Nest container, or replace a "
"real implementation with the mock object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/dependency-injection.rst:43
msgid ""
"In order to inject a custom provider, we use the ``@Inject()`` decorator."
" This decorator takes a single argument - the token."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/dependency-injection.rst:62
msgid ""
"info **Hint** The ``@Inject()`` decorator is imported from "
"``@nestjs/common`` package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/dependency-injection.rst:65
msgid ""
"When you want to override a default provider’s value, let’s say, you’d "
"like to force Nest to use a mock ``CatsService`` due to testing purposes,"
" you can simply use an existing class as a token."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/dependency-injection.rst:85
msgid ""
"In above example, the ``CatsService`` will be overridden by a passed "
"``mockCatsService`` mock object. It means, that Nest instead of creating "
"``CatsService`` instance manually, will treat this provider as resolved "
"already, and use ``mockCatsService`` as its representative value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/dependency-injection.rst:91
msgid "Use class"
msgstr "Use class"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/dependency-injection.rst:93
msgid ""
"The ``useClass`` syntax allows you using different class per chosen "
"factors. For example, we have an abstract (or default) ``ConfigService`` "
"class. Depending on the current environment, Nest should use a different "
"implementation of the configuration service."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/dependency-injection.rst:115
msgid ""
"warning **Notice** Instead of a custom token, we have used the "
"``ConfigService`` class, and therefore we have overridden the default "
"implementation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/dependency-injection.rst:119
msgid ""
"In this case, even if any class depends on ``ConfigService``, Nest will "
"inject an instance of the provided class (``DevelopmentConfigService`` or"
" ``ProductionConfigService``) instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/dependency-injection.rst:124
msgid "Use factory"
msgstr "Use factory"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/dependency-injection.rst:126
msgid ""
"The ``useFactory`` is a way of creating providers **dynamically**. The "
"actual provider will be equal to a returned value of the factory "
"function. The factory function can either depend on several different "
"providers or stay completely independent. It means that factory may "
"accept arguments, that Nest will resolve and pass during the "
"instantiation process. Additionally, this function can return value "
"**asynchronously**. It’s explained in more detail here. Use it when your "
"provider has to be dynamically calculated or in case to resolve an "
"asynchronous operation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/dependency-injection.rst:169
msgid ""
"info **Hint** If your factory needs other providers, you have to pass "
"their tokens inside the ``inject`` array. Nest will pass instances as "
"arguments of the function in the same order."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/dependency-injection.rst:174
msgid "Use existing"
msgstr "Use existing"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/dependency-injection.rst:176
msgid ""
"The ``useExisting`` allows you creating aliases for existing providers. "
"For example, the token ``AliasedLoggerService`` is an alias for "
"``LoggerService``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/dependency-injection.rst:197
msgid ""
"info **Hint** The instance of ``LoggerService`` will be equal to the "
"instance defined by ``AliasedLoggerService`` token."
msgstr ""

